
My_AWS_PRACTICALs — AWS 3-Tier Highly Available Architecture Explanation
Project Overview
My_AWS_PRACTICALs is a secure, highly available, and scalable AWS 3-tier web application architecture. The project was designed to demonstrate real-world cloud architecture skills using core AWS services such as Amazon VPC, EC2, Application Load Balancer, Auto Scaling Group, Route 53, ACM, S3, IAM, NAT Gateway, Internet Gateway, and Amazon RDS MySQL.
The architecture separates public-facing resources from private backend resources. Users access the application through a custom domain name, while the application servers and database remain protected inside private subnets.
The main goal of this architecture is to demonstrate how a production-style application can be deployed securely on AWS with high availability, scalability, and proper network isolation.

High-Level Architecture Flow
The application traffic flows in this order:
Users access the application through a custom domain.
Route 53 resolves the domain name.
Traffic enters AWS through the Internet Gateway.
The Application Load Balancer receives HTTPS traffic.
The ALB terminates SSL/TLS using an ACM certificate.
The ALB forwards traffic to the Target Group over HTTP port 80.
The Target Group routes traffic only to healthy EC2 instances.
The EC2 instances are managed by an Auto Scaling Group across private subnets.
EC2 instances communicate securely with Amazon RDS MySQL on port 3306.
EC2 instances access Amazon S3 using IAM role-based permissions.
Private EC2 instances access the internet through the NAT Gateway for updates and package installations.

1. Users / Clients
The users represent anyone accessing the application through a browser or mobile device.
Users send an HTTPS request to:
https://myawspractical.com
This request is encrypted because HTTPS is enabled using an SSL/TLS certificate from AWS Certificate Manager.
Why this matters:
Users should never access backend servers directly. They should only access the application through a controlled public entry point.

2. Amazon Route 53

Amazon Route 53 is used as the DNS service for the domain.
When users type the domain name, Route 53 resolves it and points the request to the Application Load Balancer.
Why Route 53 was used:
Route 53 provides reliable DNS routing and integrates smoothly with AWS services like ALB and ACM.
Explanation:
Route 53 does not host the application. Its job is to translate the domain name into the correct AWS endpoint.

3. AWS Certificate Manager

AWS Certificate Manager provides the SSL/TLS certificate used to secure the application with HTTPS.
The certificate is attached to the HTTPS listener on the Application Load Balancer.
Why ACM was used:
ACM removes the need to manually manage SSL certificates. It also supports automatic renewal.
Important point:
ACM is not part of the direct traffic path. It is attached to the ALB to enable secure HTTPS communication.


4. Internet Gateway
The Internet Gateway is attached to the VPC and allows public subnet resources to communicate with the internet.
In this architecture, the Application Load Balancer is placed in public subnets, so it needs internet connectivity through the Internet Gateway.
Why Internet Gateway was used:
Without an Internet Gateway, users from the internet cannot reach the public-facing ALB.

5. Public Subnets
The public subnets are located in two Availability Zones:
Public Subnet A — 10.0.1.0/24
Public Subnet B — 10.0.2.0/24
These subnets contain internet-facing resources such as:
Application Load Balancer
NAT Gateway
Why public subnets were used:
Public subnets are used for resources that must communicate with the internet.

6. Application Load Balancer 
The Application Load Balancer is deployed to distribute traffic between the two public subnets.
It receives HTTPS traffic from users and distributes requests to healthy backend EC2 instances.
Why ALB was used:
The ALB improves availability, distributes traffic, supports health checks, and prevents users from accessing EC2 instances directly.
 
Traffic flow:
Users → Route 53 → Internet Gateway → ALB
The ALB receives traffic on:
HTTPS 443
Then forwards traffic internally to the backend over:
HTTP 80

7. SSL Termination at ALB
SSL termination happens at the Application Load Balancer.
This means the user connects securely to the ALB using HTTPS, but the ALB forwards traffic internally to EC2 using HTTP.
Flow:
Browser → HTTPS 443 → ALB → HTTP 80 → EC2
Why this was done:
It centralizes certificate management at the ALB level and keeps the backend EC2 instances simpler.

8. Target Group
The Target Group sits between the ALB and the EC2 instances.
It contains the registered EC2 instances and performs health checks.
Why Target Group was used:
The Target Group ensures the ALB only sends traffic to healthy EC2 instances.
If an EC2 instance becomes unhealthy, the ALB stops sending traffic to it.

9. Auto Scaling Group
The Auto Scaling Group manages the EC2 instances in the private subnets.
It ensures that the desired number of EC2 instances are always running.
In this architecture:
Minimum capacity: 2
Desired capacity: 2
Maximum capacity: 4
Why ASG was used:
ASG provides self-healing and scalability.
If one EC2 instance fails, the ASG replaces it automatically. If traffic increases, the ASG can launch more instances.

10. Private Subnets
The private subnets are:
Private Subnet A — 10.0.3.0/24
Private Subnet B — 10.0.4.0/24
These subnets contain:
EC2 application servers
RDS database layer
Why private subnets were used:
Backend resources should not be exposed directly to the public internet.
The EC2 instances receive traffic only from the ALB, and the database receives traffic only from the EC2 security group.

11. Amazon EC2 Instances
The EC2 instances host the web application.
They are placed inside private subnets and managed by the Auto Scaling Group.
They do not have direct public access.
Why EC2 was used:
EC2 provides compute capacity to run the web application.
Why EC2 was placed in private subnets:
This prevents direct public access and improves security.

12. NAT Gateway
The NAT Gateway is placed inside a public subnet.
Private EC2 instances use the NAT Gateway to access the internet for:
package updates
software installations
external API calls
downloading dependencies
Important:
The NAT Gateway allows outbound traffic from private instances, but it does not allow inbound traffic from the internet to reach those instances.
Flow:
Private EC2 → NAT Gateway → Internet Gateway → Internet
Why one NAT Gateway was used:
A single NAT Gateway was used for cost optimization in this lab environment.
In production, one NAT Gateway per Availability Zone is recommended for higher availability.

13. Amazon RDS MySQL

Amazon RDS MySQL is used as the relational database layer.
The database is deployed inside private subnets using a dedicated DB subnet group.
It has:
Primary DB
Standby DB for Multi-AZ resilience
Why RDS was used:
RDS provides managed database services, including backups, patching, availability, and failover options.
Why RDS was placed in private subnets:
The database should never be directly accessible from the internet.
Only EC2 instances are allowed to connect to it.
Database traffic:
EC2 → RDS MySQL
Port:
MySQL 3306

14. Amazon S3

Amazon S3 is used for object storage.
It can store:
images
static files
logs
backups
deployment files
S3 is shown outside the VPC because S3 is not deployed inside a subnet.
Why S3 was used:
S3 provides durable, scalable, and cost-effective object storage.
How EC2 accesses S3:
EC2 instances access S3 using IAM role-based permissions, not hardcoded access keys.

15. IAM Role
An IAM role is attached to the EC2 instances.
This role allows EC2 to securely access AWS services such as:
S3
Systems Manager
Why IAM role was used:
IAM roles provide temporary secure credentials to EC2 instances.
This avoids storing AWS access keys directly on the server.

16. Security Groups
Security groups control traffic between the different layers.
ALB Security Group
Allows:
HTTPS 443 from the internet
HTTP 80 if redirect is enabled
EC2 Security Group
Allows:
HTTP 80 only from the ALB security group
RDS Security Group
Allows:
MySQL 3306 only from the EC2 security group
Why this is important:
Each layer only accepts traffic from the layer that should communicate with it.
This follows the principle of least privilege.

17. High Availability Design
The architecture uses two Availability Zones.
Resources are distributed across:
Availability Zone A
Availability Zone B
The ALB spans both public subnets, and the Auto Scaling Group launches EC2 instances across both private subnets.
The RDS layer also uses a primary and standby database setup.
Why this matters:
If one Availability Zone has an issue, the application can continue running from the other Availability Zone.

18. Main Traffic Flow Summary
The main user request flow is:
Users → Route 53 → Internet Gateway → Application Load Balancer → Target Group → Auto Scaling Group → EC2 Instances → RDS MySQL
The storage flow is:
EC2 Instances ↔ Amazon S3
The outbound internet flow is:
Private EC2 → NAT Gateway → Internet Gateway → Internet

19. Why This Architecture Is Secure
This architecture is secure because:
Users cannot directly access EC2 instances.
EC2 instances are inside private subnets.
RDS is inside private subnets.
RDS only accepts traffic from EC2.
EC2 only accepts traffic from the ALB.
S3 access is controlled through IAM roles.
HTTPS is enforced using ACM and ALB.
Public access is limited to the ALB only.

20. Why This Architecture Is Scalable
The architecture is scalable because:
The ALB distributes traffic across multiple EC2 instances.
The Auto Scaling Group can add or remove EC2 instances based on demand.
S3 scales automatically for object storage.
RDS can be scaled vertically or configured with Multi-AZ for availability.

21. Why This Architecture Is Highly Available
The architecture is highly available because:
It uses multiple Availability Zones.
The ALB spans two public subnets.
EC2 instances run across two private subnets.
The ASG replaces failed instances automatically.
RDS uses primary and standby database architecture.
Route 53 provides reliable DNS routing.

22.  Explanation
My_AWS_PRACTICALs is a secure and highly available AWS 3-tier architecture designed to simulate a real-world production deployment.
The architecture uses a custom VPC with public and private subnets across multiple Availability Zones. Public subnets host internet-facing services such as the Application Load Balancer and NAT Gateway, while private subnets host backend EC2 application servers and the RDS MySQL database.
Users access the application through a custom domain managed by Route 53. HTTPS traffic is secured using an ACM SSL/TLS certificate attached to the ALB. The ALB forwards traffic to a Target Group, which routes requests only to healthy EC2 instances managed by an Auto Scaling Group.
The EC2 instances communicate securely with Amazon RDS MySQL over port 3306 and access Amazon S3 for object storage using IAM role-based permissions. Private EC2 instances use the NAT Gateway for outbound internet access without being directly exposed to the internet.
This project demonstrates strong understanding of AWS networking, security, scalability, high availability, DNS, HTTPS, IAM, storage, and database integration.

